<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A bill approved by the Senate Finance Committee would give more than 100 years 
of amnesty to fraternal groups, taverns and convenience stores for past-due 
levies under a little-known tax on liquor retailers. Protests over the tax had 
mounted after a Pennsylvania Elks lodge got a $9,000 bill for 50 years of 
non-payment. The measure would prohibit the federal government from collecting 
unpaid balances and penalties on the 123-year-old tax if they accrued before 
Jan. 1, 1985, according to Sen. John Heinz (R-Pa.). Although the tax has been 
on the books since 1866, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms says that 
up to 40% of retailers had never heard of it until the agency began a vigorous 
collection effort last year. 
</P>
